{{Short description|Hindu personification of death}} [[Image:Yama's Court and Hell.jpg|thumb|Yama's court.|260x260px]] '''Mṛtyu''' ({{lang-sa|मृत्यु|lit=Death|translit=Mṛtyu}}), is a [[Sanskrit]] word meaning [[death]]. Mṛtyu, or Death, is often [[Death (personification)|personified as]] the deities ''Mara'' (मर) and ''[[Yama]]'' (यम) in [[Dharmic religions]] such as [[Hinduism]] and [[Buddhism]]. * [[Mara (Hindu goddess)]], the goddess of death according to [[Hindu mythology]]. *'''Mṛtyu-māra''' as death in Buddhism or [[Mara (demon)|Māra]], a "demon" of the Buddhist cosmology, the personification of Temptation. *'''[[Yama]]''' ({{lang-sa|यम}}) is the god of death and the underworld in Hinduism and Buddhism. **[[Yama (Hinduism)|Yama]] in Hinduism. **[[Yama (East Asia)|Yama]] in Buddhism.
==Etymology== The Vedic ''mṛtyú'', along with [[Avestan]] ''mərəθiiu'' and [[Old Persian]] ''məršiyu'' comes from the Proto-Indo-Iranian word for death, ''*mr̥tyú-'', which is ultimately derived from the Indo-European root ''*mer-'' ("to die") and thus is further related to [[Latin]] ''mors''.
==Literature==
=== Vedas === Mrtyu is invoked in the hymns of the [[Rigveda]]:<ref>{{Cite web |last=www.wisdomlib.org |date=2021-08-27 |title=Rig Veda 10.18.1 [English translation] |url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/rig-veda-english-translation/d/doc838689.html |access-date=2022-11-04 |website=www.wisdomlib.org |language=en}}</ref> {{Blockquote|text=Depart, Mṛtyu, by a different path; by that which is your own, and distinct from the path of the gods; Ispeak to you who have eyes, who have ears; do no harm to our offspring, nor to our male progeny.|title=[[Rigveda]]|source=Hymn 10.18.1}}
=== Upanishads === The [[Brhadaranyaka Upanishad]] (a mystical appendix to the [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] and likely the oldest of the Upanishads) has a [[creation myth]] where ''{{IAST|Mṛtyu}}'' "Death" takes the shape of a horse, and includes an identification of the [[Ashvamedha]] horse sacrifice with the Sun:<ref>implicitly, in ''{{IAST|eṣa vā aśvamedho ya eṣa tapati}}'' "verily, that Ashvamedha is that which gives out heat [''tap-'']"</ref> :{{Blockquote|text=Then he became a horse (ashva), because it swelled (ashvat), and was fit for sacrifice (medhya); and this is why the horse-sacrifice is called Ashva-medha [...] Therefore the sacrificers offered up the purified horse belonging to Prajapati, (as dedicated) to all the deities. Verily the shining sun [ye tapati] is the Asvamedha, and his body is the year; Agni is the sacrificial fire (arka), and these worlds are his bodies. These two are the sacrificial fire and the Asvamedha-sacrifice, and they are again one deity, viz. Death.|title=[[Brhadaranyaka Upanishad]]|source=Hymn 1.2.7}}
=== Padma Purana === Mrtyu fights in the war between the [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]] and the [[Asura|asuras]] in the legend of [[Jalandhara]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=www.wisdomlib.org |date=2019-09-26 |title=War Between Gods and Demons [Chapter 5] |url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/the-padma-purana/d/doc365436.html |access-date=2022-11-04 |website=www.wisdomlib.org |language=en}}</ref>
=== Mahabharata === The [[Mahabharata]] references a legend regarding a dispute between [[Time in Hindu mythology|Time]], Mrityu, Yama, [[Ikshvaku]], and a [[Brahmin|Brahmana]]. Mrityu is female in this legend.<ref>{{Cite web |last=www.wisdomlib.org |date=2021-08-17 |title=Section CXCIX [Mahabharata, English] |url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/the-mahabharata-mohan/d/doc826157.html |access-date=2022-11-04 |website=www.wisdomlib.org |language=en}}</ref>
