{{Short description|Class of deities in Hinduism}}
The '''maharajikas''' ({{Lang-sa|महाराजिक|translit=Mahārājika}}) refers to a [[Gana|class]] of minor [[Devata|deities]] in [[Hinduism]], numbering 220 or 236 members.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Dowson |first=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9RD-AQAAQBAJ&dq=Maharajikas&pg=PA193 |title=A Classical Dictionary of Hindu Mythology and Religion, Geography, History and Literature |date=2013-11-05 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-39036-4 |pages=193 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Kapoor |first=Subodh |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HJ6O8nwsFWgC&dq=maharajikas+puranas&pg=PA240 |title=A Dictionary of Hinduism: Including Its Mythology, Religion, History, Literature, and Pantheon |date=2004 |publisher=Cosmo Publications |isbn=978-81-7755-874-6 |pages=240 |language=en}}</ref>
== Description == The [[Puranas]] feature the maharajikas among the nine classes (''gaṇas'') of deities, among the [[adityas]], [[rudras]], [[Vasu|vasus]], [[visvedevas]], [[Tushita|tushitas]], [[abhasvaras]], anilas, and the [[sadhyas]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Dalal |first=Roshen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=87k0AwAAQBAJ&dq=Maharajikas+gana&pg=PT448 |title=The Religions of India: A Concise Guide to Nine Major Faiths |date=2014-04-18 |publisher=Penguin UK |isbn=978-81-8475-396-7 |pages=448 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Vettem Mani |url=http://archive.org/details/yqck_puranic-encyolopaedia-vettem-mani |title=Puranic Encyolopaedia Vettem Mani |pages=892}}</ref> They are sometimes referred to as a class of the [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]],<ref>{{Cite book |last=Williams |first=George M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7LOZfwCDpEC&dq=maharajikas+deities&pg=PA112 |title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology |date=2008-03-27 |publisher=OUP USA |isbn=978-0-19-533261-2 |pages=112 |language=en}}</ref> or the gaṇadevas.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Vaidik Sudha |url=http://archive.org/details/Puranencyclopedia |title=Puran Encyclopedia |date=2020-06-17 |pages=892}}</ref> According to the [[Shiva Purana]], the maharajikas serve as the attendants of [[Shiva]], under the command of [[Ganesha]]. They are regarded to reside on the Gaṇaparvata mountain, situated on [[Mount Kailash|Kailasha]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Prof. J. L. Shastri |url=http://archive.org/details/siva-purana-part-1 |title=The Siva Purana Part 1 |date=1950 |pages=271}}</ref>
